The most unexpected finding from session one was not related to the math at all — it was related to Maddie's almost immediate command of the voice function. It took only two turns for her to fall into a rhythm: pausing the voice function to work out the problem on scratch paper, then engaging in spoken dialogue with the model, then looping back again when she was ready for the next problem. She was able to figure out how to pause the voice function after being shown how to start it, and upon noticing that it was picking up ambient noise, she began pausing it consistently for the remainder of the session. This behavior mirrors what the session debrief later identified as a core strength:  Maddie's tendency to self-correct quickly when she catches an error in her thinking or environment. The fact that this self-correction happened before the math portion of the session even began indicates that this behavior is part of her natural disposition and not something that she learned in session while working with the tutor.

Two moments in the session revealed a consistent pattern in Maddie's learning style that the debrief identified but did not fully analyze. When the model introduced a visual image of a box to explain volume, Maddie was able to immediately connect her knowledge of volume to the mental image the model had created. She reacted with a visible jump, said 'oh I get it' to herself, and paused the model to work the problem out on scratch paper. Later in the session, the model did not use a visual mental image when asking Maddie to split ⅓ in half, and she struggled to make the connection, resulting in the model having to supply the answer after several attempts. Maddie then spent several minutes silently processing the answer before she was ready to move on. The two incidents communicate that Maddie is a strong visual spatial learner who likely needs visual cues to enhance her problem-solving capabilities. This finding prompted a direct refinement to the session prompt — specifically the addition of Rule 11, which instructs the model to incorporate a mental image or visual analogy if Maddie appears stuck before asking further guiding questions. This finding also reveals a meaningful limitation of the AI-generated debrief: because the model is unable to track Maddie's responses visually, it could not connect her success on the volume problem to the presence of a visual scaffold, nor her struggle on the fraction problem to the absence of one. That connection was only visible to the in-room observer.

The second observer-only finding involved Maddie's reaction when the model explained her reasoning back to her after she had solved a problem independently. When the model asked her to elaborate and then reflected her own reasoning back to her, Maddie advocated for herself by saying 'I got that without your help though' to the tutor. At this point she was visibly exasperated and turned to the observer for validation, before pausing the model and saying out loud to the computer screen, 'I got that. This is just a computer. So, I can forgive you for that.' This reveals that Maddie has high metacognitive awareness of her own performance and an ability to emotionally self-regulate while staying in a grounded line of thinking about what the tutor actually is. Her turning to the observer for validation before self-regulating suggests that the presence of a trusted adult in the room functioned as a secure base from which Maddie could express her frustration before self-regulating and moving on. This connects directly to the observer's background in MFS and the prompt design including principles from secure base attachment theory. This observation prompted a refinement to Rule 9 of the session prompt, which was updated to reflect Maddie's need for clear recognition of skill when it is warranted.

Research Question 1: *Can a structured AI tutoring session reduce the apparent gap between Maddie's demonstrated knowledge and her test performance?*

Status: Too early to determine. Data from session one confirmed that the performance gap appears to stem primarily from test anxiety and format unfamiliarity rather than a knowledge deficit — consistent with the pre-experiment hypothesis. However, whether the intervention is successfully targeting that gap will not be measurable until Maddie's SOL score is available. The restructuring of the prompt prior to session two — specifically the addition of multiple choice format with vocal reasoning — is designed to more directly simulate test conditions while preserving the low-stakes environment, and may better target the anxiety response that appears to be the core variable.

Research Question 2: *Does the debrief report generated by the AI accurately identify the nature of the performance gap — anxiety vs. knowledge deficit vs. format unfamiliarity?*

Status: Partially confirmed. The debrief accurately identified the nature of Maddie's performance gap, assessing that her struggles appear to reflect a confidence and recall deficit under cold testing conditions rather than a lack of foundational knowledge — consistent with the pre-experiment hypothesis. However, the debrief was unable to accurately assess Maddie's visual spatial learning preference, as the model had no access to Maddie's physical responses during the session. The most diagnostically significant moments — her visible reaction to the box visualization and her prolonged silent processing of the fraction problem — were only observable to the in-room human observer. This finding suggests that AI-generated debriefs are most accurate when evaluating verbal and textual reasoning, but require human observer supplementation to capture the full picture of a student's learning profile.

Research Question 3: *What does a first LLM interaction look like for a child with this cognitive profile, and how does she engage with a system designed around her specific needs?*

Status: Highly informative. Maddie appeared completely at ease with the LLM tutor and was enthusiastic about using it for SOL preparation. She learned to operate the voice function almost intuitively, and remained engaged for nearly an hour — significantly beyond the twenty minute minimum suggested by the observer. She stayed open and conversational throughout, consistent with the observer's instructions, and demonstrated healthy self-advocacy when the model over-explained her own reasoning back to her. The session ended on Maddie's own terms, when she indicated to the tutor that she was finished. These findings suggest that this type of interaction may be uniquely suited to her cognitive profile. Curious, self-aware, and intrinsically motivated learners may be particularly well positioned to make meaningful educational progress through tools that employ Socratic dialogue and adapt to the student in real time — a hypothesis that warrants further investigation across additional sessions and student profiles.

Session one was remarkably successful. Maddie stayed engaged significantly longer than anticipated, participated honestly and openly, learned the interface quickly, advocated for herself when needed, and ended the session autonomously — outcomes that suggest strong initial alignment between the intervention design and her learning profile. The primary area requiring refinement was question format. Because Maddie immediately selected voice mode to avoid typing, the session diverged from the cold, written conditions of the actual SOL. This was addressed prior to session two through a prompt revision incorporating multiple choice questions with vocal reasoning — a hybrid format designed to reintroduce test simulation while preserving the conversational dynamic that kept her engaged.

Two questions will guide observation in session two: first, whether engagement remains high once the novelty of the first session has faded; and second, how the introduction of multiple choice format affects the nature of Maddie's interaction with the tutor.

A final methodological note warranting consideration for future experimentation: the most diagnostically significant finding from session one — Maddie's visual spatial learning preference — was observable only to the in-room human observer and could not be captured by the AI debrief. This type of preference is unlikely to be accurately self-reported by a child. However, it may be self-reportable by an adult learner, suggesting that a pre-session learning style self-assessment could partially close the observer-dependency gap identified in this session. This represents a potentially valuable methodological refinement for future iterations of this intervention across different student profiles.

